accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: This collection is open to research.
When conducting research within The Corcoran Archives collections, please be advised of the following restrictions:
Records of the Board of Trustees (RG 1.0) and records of the Office of the Director (RG 2.0) are closed to research for 25 years from the date of creation.
Development records are closed to research (RG 3.2).

Access to student records is governed by the federal Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act (FERPA), which protects the privacy of student education records. Student records are closed for the lifetime of the student, and are presumed to be open 75 years after the date of record creation (RG 9.0 Series 4).
Personnel and financial records are closed for 50 years from date of record creation (RG 4.0).
Please see the Public Services and Instruction Librarian for assistance.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: The Corcoran Institution Board of Trustees donated these records to The George Washington University in 2016.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Organized into 6 series: Early Conservation records; Harold F. Cross records; Russell J. Quandt records; Robert Scott Wiles records; Dare Myers Hartwell records; and Conservation files transferred from the National Gallery of Art.

bioghist.head: Historical narrative
bioghist.p: The following history was prepared in 2019 by George Washington University SCRC staff with the support of the Luce Foundation.
According to accounts in the Corcoran Gallery of art Directors' records, paintings in the collection began to be sent out for repairs and touch-ups as early as 1886.

In 1946, the need for a regular program of care and conservation of the works of art in the collection was stressed during Board of Trustees proceedings, and in 1948 the Board of Trustees authorized the appointment of Harold F. Cross as the staff conservator, as well as the "necessary renovation and equipment" for a conservation laboratory. In 1951, Russell J. Quandt began his twenty-year affiliation with the Corcoran as its conservator. Robert Scott Wiles was the affiliated conservator from 1971-1983.

Prior to 1983, the Gallery's painting conservation was conducted by a private conservator using the Corcoran's facilities on a contractual basis. In order to better serve the needs of the collection, in 1983 the Corcoran established a conservation lab and hired full-time staff conservator Dare Hartwell. Dare Hartwell was responsible for the general care of the entire collection and treatment of paintings.

The conservation department's initial focus was on equipping the lab. Through matching grants from The National Endowment for the Arts from 1983-1986, the Gallery purchased over $45,000 worth of new conservation equipment. During this time, the Corcoran also completed a major climate control project that allowed for improvements in control of the environmental conditions within the building.

Between 1984 and 1987, Dare Hartwell conducted a general condition survey of all collections, storage and museum environments. While Hartwell treated paintings in the collection as time permitted in the course of her duties, the Corcoran obtained additional grants throughout the 1980s and 1990s to hire and contract outside professionals to survey and treat other types of objects in the collection. Specific grants from a variety of organizations including Getty Trust, Institute of Museum Services, and The National Endowment for the Arts allowed for the treatment of sculptures, works on paper, and textiles. Throughout all grant projects, the Corcoran Gallery curators worked closely with Hartwell and the contracted conservators.

In 1989, Dare Hartwell initiated a multi-step restoration project of the Salon Dore, the Corcoran's 18th-century French period room donated to the Corcoran in 1926 as part of the bequest of Montana Senator William A. Clark. The project included the removal of layers of dirt and overpainting from the walls and ceiling, restoration of damaged gold leaf by specialized craftspeople, and reproduction of the curtains weaved by French fabric house Tassinari & Chatel. The project completed with installation of the new curtains in 2001.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: Please include the following elements in your citation: document description and date, record group number, collection name, box and folder numbers, Special Collections Research Center, George Washington University Libraries, Washington, DC.

For example: "Meeting Minutes, Corcoran Board of Trustees," 1902. RG 1, Corcoran Gallery of Art board of trustees records, box 4, folder 7. Special Collections Research Center, George Washington University Libraries, Washington, DC.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This record group contains records generated by the office of the Corcoran conservator over the lifetime of its operation, beginning with independent conservators contracted for work in the Corcoran Gallery building and collections. Material types include condition reports for works of art, conservation journals, correspondence, photographs, and charts documenting the environment in the galleries. Records date from 1882-2019.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p:
To the extent that the institution owns copyright, the donor has assigned the copyright in its works to The George Washington University; however, copyright in other items in this collection may be held by their respective creators. For activities that the researcher determines fall under fair use as defined under U.S. Copyright Law, no permission to cite or publish is required. Please contact Special Collections if the copyright status of the materials you wish to reuse is unclear. Staff will provide additional information.
For re-use of materials in the collection not created by the donor, researchers are responsible for determining who may hold materials' copyrights, determining if the intended re-use falls under fair use, and obtaining approval from the copyright holder if the intended use does not fall under fair use. For such materials, researchers do not need anything further from The George Washington University's Special Collections Research Center.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains two small notebooks containing early conservation records of L.J. Kohlmer, index cards created in 1977 containing an alphabetically-indexed transcription of the information contained in the L.J. Kohlmer notebooks, and correspondence of Associate Curator Eleanor Swenson related to conservation before the hiring of Corcoran's first contractor conservator Harold F. Cross. Records date from 1932-1977.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains records created by Harold F. Cross, first conservator for the Corcoran who worked under contract from 1948-1951. Materials include a time log for conservation work, conservation notes, and agreements between Cross and private art owners for conservation treatment and photographing of their artworks. Records date from 1948-1951.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains records created by conservator Russell J. Quandt in the course of his twenty-year affiliation with the Corcoran Gallery from 1951-1971. Materials include daily conservation notes, conservation reports, artwork condition forms, conservation billing records, agreements between Quandt and private art owners for conservation treatment, and photographs. Records date from 1950-1971.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains records created by conservator Robert Scott Wiles in the course of his position as contract conservator from 1971 to approximately 1983. Materials include quarterly and annual reports prepared by Wiles for the Board of Trustees, budget records for conservation treatments, and files for individual works of art treated by Wiles during his tenure. Records date from 1971-1983.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains quarterly and annual reports prepared by Wiles for the Board of Trustees and budget records for conservation treatments. Records date from 1971-1979.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains a file of cards and postcards sent by artists to Robert Scott Wiles during his tenure as conservator at the Corcoran Gallery. Materials date from 1971-1982.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This series is arranged in 6 subseries: Hygrothermograph charts; Building exterior condition and restoration records; Conservation grants and financial records; Salon Dore restoration files; Nature Conservancy exhibition files; and Dare Myers Hartwell Conservation Consulting Services treatment reports

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains records created by Corcoran staff conservator Dare Myers Hartwell in the course of her tenure at the Corcoran Gallery from 1983 to approximately 2014. Materials include hygrothermograph charts measuring temperature and relative humidity in the Corcoran Gallery, reports on restoration of the building's exterior, records and reports of various conservation grants, financial records, records related to the ongoing restoration of the Salon Dore, and condition reports for artworks returned from loan. The final subseries in this series contains reports and work undertaken by Hartwell as a contractor after she had retired. Records date from 1982-2019.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains weekly hygrothermograph charts that recorded temperature and relative humidity in rooms of the Corcoran building, including the Archives, Art Storage, Cafe Storage, Conservation Lab, Salon Dore, and various galleries. The records date from 1982-2011, with gaps in 1984-1989, 1992-1998, and 2002-2006.
